 with real listeners. The station stream is HTTP while the site is HTTPS, so two Cloudflare Workers safely re-serve the audio and now-playing feed for modern browsers.</p><p>The project also includes an authenticated owner-admin area, play history, listener feedback, first-party analytics, CSP validation and automated authentication tests.</p><ul class="tag-list" aria-label="Coast Internet Radio project skills"><li>Cloudflare Workers</li><li>Netlify Functions</li><li>Netlify Blobs</li><li>Session auth and CSRF</li><li>First-party analytics</li><li>Content Security Policy</li></ul><div class="project-card-actions"><a class="button button-primary" href="https://coastinternetradio.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View live site</a><a class="button button-secondary" href="coast-internet-radio-case-study.html">Read case study</a><a class="button button-ghost" href="https://github.com/JamieP-205/coast-internet-radio" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub repo</a></div></div></article><article class="project-card project-card-production"><figure class="project-card-media"><img src="assets/talk-with-jamie-home.jpg" alt="Screenshot of Talk With Jamie showing the disclosed AI welcome screen with log in, create account and guest options."></figure><div class="project-card-body"><p class="eyebrow">Privacy-conscious serverless app</p><h3>Talk With Jamie</h3><p>An AI chat with guest and registered accounts, saved conversations and a private admin side. The important engineering problem is access control: public and private users receive context from different retrieval boundaries enforced in code rather than left to a prompt.</p><p>Private source material is not committed or included in the static deployment. Signed sessions, storage, rate limits and automated checks sit behind Netlify Functions.</p><ul class="tag-list" aria-label="Talk With Jamie project skills"><li>Netlify Functions</li><li>Authentication</li><li>Netlify Blobs</li><li>Context retrieval</li><li>Privacy boundaries</li><li>Automated tests</li></ul><div class="project-card-actions"><a class="button button-primary" href="https://talkwithjamie.netlify.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View live project</a><a class="button button-secondary" href="talk-with-jamie-case-study.html">Read case study</a><a class="button button-ghost" href="https://github.com/JamieP-205/talk-with-jamie" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub repo</a></div></div></article><article class="project-card project-card-production"><figure class="project-card-media"><img src="assets/local-web-fix-home.jpg" alt="Screenshot of the Local Web Fix homepage showing the free check offer and desktop layout."></figure><div class="project-card-body"><p class="eyebrow">Small service website</p><h3>Local Web Fix</h3><p>A clear, mobile-first service site for practical website and online-information fixes. A business can submit a public link for a free check before deciding whether paid work is worthwhile.</p><p>The strongest part is the boundary design: prices are visible, the scope states what I will not touch and the enquiry flow never asks a client for passwords.</p><ul class="tag-list" aria-label="Local Web Fix project skills"><li>Service website</li><li>Mobile-first design</li><li>Contact flow</li><li>Clear pricing</li><li>Privacy wording</li><li>Small business UX</li></ul><div class="project-card-actions"><a class="button button-primary" href="https://localwebfix.co.uk" target="_